│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ **2. Root Cause:**                                                                                                                                                                       │
│ A `select` instruction with a vector condition (e.g., `<N x i1>`) requires that its true and false value operands also be vectors of length `N`. In the failing example, the original    │
│ `select` has a `<2 x i1>` condition and `<2 x float>` operands, which is valid. The `shufflevector` instruction, however, produces a `<4 x float>` result. The `FoldOpIntoSelect` logic  │
│ attempts to create a new `select` instruction like `select <2 x i1> %cond, <4 x float> ..., <4 x float> ...`. This is invalid because the condition vector length (2) does not match the │
│ value vector length (4), leading to an assertion failure in the `SelectInst` constructor.                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ **3. Proposed Fix:**                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ The fix is to prevent `FoldOpIntoSelect` from being called when the vector length of the `shufflevector`'s result type is different from the vector length of the `select`'s condition.  │
